Three cheetahs of ice: Three cheetah cubs were born in Iran
The world's fastest animal is victims of cruel hunts, forts and fatal road accidents across the Islamic Republic
As a result, their number dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asian cheeps recently emerged into the world in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
It is a rare birth, which slightly improves the tragic condition of the endangered animal in the country due to the droughts, hunters and fatal road accidents.
This is the first birth of cheetah in cavity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency Irna reported that the veterinary team, which is responsible for the Turan National Park in the northern Samnan Province, decided on a Caesarean birth in captivity.
It was also noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have been documented in seven different provinces in the country.
Due to the danger of their extinction, the UN carried out a defense plan for them back in 2001.
Now, Iran hopes that the new cubs will be able to bring about an increase in the population of the cheetah population in the future.
In January, the deputy minister of environmental affairs in Iran, Hassan Akbari, said that the population of the cheetahs in the country was dramatically reduced from 100 cheetahs in 2010 to only 12 cheetahs.
"Their situation is extremely serious," Akbari said, noting that the cheetahs fell victim to drought in their living areas, hunting and even road accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world capable of reaching a speed of about 100 km/h.
The cheetahs can be found in different places across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your car: We checked the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify began to try her luck in the world of hardware.
After years of development - Car Thing was exposed and launched as a small experiment in the US •
We put our hands on the first device in Israel •
Vision: Make your old cars smart
The Car Thing is Spotify’s first hardware product, and is built specifically to provide a solution for people with old cars.
A few weeks ago, I got an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available for individual experimenters in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the shipment was outstanding, since our home car broke down and we had to drive for a few days with an alternative vehicle with an old system.
After two weeks of entertaining, I understood how Car Thing can easily become an integral part of many people’s system.
And on the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty about global launch, I believe that many would already prefer to use other solutions.
From Idea to Reality
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users began to receive an interesting offer in their email box - the possibility of purchasing a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connection, which will make any old car system smart.
The rumors slowly faded until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company is planning to soon introduce a new car product that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors returned to the headlines again after the music service was updated with the vehicle mode – the same one we know today from the app – which is activated once the smartphone detects a connection to the system in the car.
Two years have passed since.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify revealed “Car Thing” in April, its smart system for vehicles.
Spotify has chosen to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays when it comes to shipments.
So, of course, right after the press conference, I went to the site and signed up.
Two months later, the long-awaited announcement arrived.
Reconnecting to the site will buy me the option to purchase the device with a little surprise - it will cost me nothing.
After another month of waiting, the courier finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The Car Thing
First and foremost, Spotify's device impressed me very much with the quality of its construction.
And a little smaller than my iPhone 11 and includes a large, bright and sharp touch screen in front of it.
You can also find a round button and a dial that you can rotate next to the screen to navigate between the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively thin profile and not stand out too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer that the company allow the company to change the activity so that I could control the volume of the smartphone, since I can also navigate through the touch screen.
Maybe it'll be possible to update a future version.
The device comes in a small and minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type C cable and various adapters for its installation.
Many of you probably remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radios and hide them in the drawer after getting out of the car.
The Car Thing undoubtedly restores this feeling with its construction form.
All the adapters connected to the body of the device using a magnet that was very strong, which prevented it from falling even when driving on dirt roads.
In addition, along the entire top you can find small buttons, which can be easily set to run different playlists or podcasts.
By pressing one of the buttons while hearing, or by asking the voice assistant, I set up some playlists that I hear frequently and the radio program I listen to every morning on the road.
In doing so, the feature made me feel that Car Thing is more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
From an old car to a smart car
After a fairly simple physical installation, I connected the Car Thing to electricity.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, the connection to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I arrived at the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone through Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote control, and therefore can copy all the information about our account from it.
In other words, you still have to connect your smartphone to the car, either via Bluetooth or through an AUX cable to hear the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, since like the application on a smartphone, it emphasizes the photos of the albums and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one in the app, you can find recommendations for music depending on your taste, your search screen and your personal library.
As mentioned above, you can navigate between the different screens using the touch screen or through the manual dial.
Moreover, at any given moment you can call the device's vocal assistant by saying "Hi Spotify".
Through it, you can run songs, playlists, albums and even search for podcasts.
From my experience, she recognized quite easily my voice even when the music was playing in the background and the air conditioner blew directly on the device.
This is probably thanks to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that at the moment the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time the article is published, there is no information on when such an update will arrive.
So is it worth waiting for him?
My experience of using the device was great, and it's a positive surprise to me considering it's still in the initial release phase.
Even in intensive use of long journeys, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Still, occasionally a small stutter in the interface is recorded, but I believe Spotify will handle such bugs with future version updates.
It is clear that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and among the different versions that leaked on the Internet during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I saw the Car Thing for the first time, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to designate it.
After all, his activity comes down to controlling the app on a smartphone, and not much more.
What is different from buying a car stand for a few shekels and connect it so that the smartphone is closer to us when driving?
This question is reinforced when considering that iPhones and Android devices are much stronger than Spotify, and most of the time will give the user much more functionality.
Despite all this, the more I used Car Thing, the more I realized how it could improve the driving experience.
The ability to see Waze on my smartphone screen and control music on a completely different screen, this is one I've learned to appreciate in the last two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
If so, will it be launched here in our small country as well?
Swedish company doesn't tell much right now.
She has not even shared how many experimenters to the device it is currently operating around the world, and how much she plans to add at the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is the price that is expected to be $79 (about NIS 255).
Meanwhile, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse into the concept that Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said there is currently no information about the device launch plan in Israel
