Did you recruit a talent for the company?
That way, you keep the competition from "hijacking" it.
The economy is still in a labor market that is largely controlled by the workers, and this is sevenfold true when it comes to the most desirable workers - the talents •
Here are some tips to help you keep it in the workplace
.
Despite the increase recorded in the past month, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to be among the lowest in the world, and in the top ten of OECD countries, with a rate of 3.5% (150.6 thousand unemployed, according to the CBS).
In other words, the economy is still in a labor market that is largely controlled by the workers, and this is quite true when it comes to the most desirable workers – the talents.
When it comes to those professionals and managers who are proven knowledge centers, experience and ability – the trends in the labor market show that the competition for them, the talents as they are referred to by the employers, still exists in full force.
This means for employers that in the current working market situation they do not have the luxury of resting on the laurels even a minute after the recruitment of a coveted talent, since once he enters the company’s gates – another company will already try to kidnap him.
In other words, the competition for talent is so fierce that many, who, even after their enlistment, will continue to receive a variety of tempting job offers, with 30% of employees not leaving for only a month from the job receipt and the start of work.
This is why intelligent employers will immediately move from the stage of recruiting the talent to its preservation stage, when the road begins first and foremost with advance preparation and take creativity in its absorption process.
An efficient, structured and thoughtful absorption process will make the talent enthusiastic about his new place of work from the very first day and even expect to come.
Here are some tips on how to prepare and manage a proper absorption process that will help in the preservation of the new talent:
It's no secret - sharing and readiness of the organization |
Share with the factors that will work with him for his recruitment, explain to them why it is essential and important to society and the role, and how you see his contribution.
A new employee who comes to a place where he is expected and understands his value will feel welcome and will strive to prove the expectations that a son hangs.
Knowledge is power - Coordination of expectations |
On the first day, the Talent held a coordination call with expectations.
Get to know his professional background and see where he sees himself in the future, so you can show him the various and unique tools that you and the workplace can provide him to get there.
We are all people – personal acquaintance |
During the absorption days try to get to know the talent beyond his professional qualities and were interested in his hobbies and interests.
A new employee who is interested and allows him to realize and express himself beyond the boundaries of his job will appreciate it and want to keep it safe.
Curiosity Progress |
Already in the absorption stage you can create attractiveness that will make the talent want to fit in quickly.
Do this not necessarily by talking bonuses and benefits, but by exposing it to an exciting field or to interesting technology, as such stimuli for creativity lead to curiosity and growing interest in the workplace.
In addition, they encouraged the talent to voice his thoughts and opinions to the various projects in the company and made it clear to him that they were important to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel – the largest placement and personnel company in Israel
Electricity in the pocket: the cost of not closing the coal stations in June - a billion shekels
Report of the Knesset Research and Information Center: Failure to close the coal stations on the date set in June 2022 is estimated at NIS 1 billion
• The Electric Company: "The policy of using fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy"
.
The economic cost for non-closing of coal stations on the date set in June 2022 is estimated at NIS 1 billion for 2022, according to a report by the Knesset Research and Information Center.
According to the report, this cost is embodied in the consumer electricity tariff, which is expected to increase in the coming months due to the coal increase.
In addition, in 2023, another amount of surplus is expected to be used in coal by about 900 thousand tons, so that this will be reflected in an additional cost to the electricity sector due to the non-closing of coal stations, assuming that the price of natural gas will remain significantly lower than the price of coal.
The report said that the significance of reducing about NIS 1 billion in the 2021 electricity tariff was a reduction of about 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for the home consumer.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the stations is about a billion shekels, and the total reduction that the home consumer could have had is about 4%.
It should be noted that in the framework of the reform in the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary of the IEC, which will establish units operated by natural gas, designed to replace the coal units 1-4 at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government decision was made in July 2018, which states that the activity of the coal production units 4-1 in the Orot Rabin power plant must be stopped.
The decision set schedules, so that the establishment of the first unit in natural gas will begin in January 2020 and its operation will begin in June 2022, and accordingly the coal-only 4-1 units will also cease to operate on this date.
The IEC said in response: “The policy of using fuels is dictated first and foremost by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the Ministry’s decisions, a policy of reducing the use of coal has been implemented in Israel for the minimum possible even when the price of coal is lower than the price of gas.”
Paying the price: everything you need to know about the interest rate increase
Cuts incessantly: Next week interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent •
How much will the mortgage payment cost?
What is recommended to do? •
All the answers
The escalating inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of more than 4% in the past year, will force the Bank of Israel to raise interest rates on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts estimates speak of a raise rate ranging from 0.25 percent to 0.5%.
If the interest rate rises by half a percent, it will already be 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This is after years, the interest rate in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate increases by hundreds of shekels the mortgage repayments and drastically burdens the households.
With the help of Shai Tzror, a mortgage expert, we checked how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate rises by half a percent - how much will the monthly payment on the mortgage increase?
A mortgage in the amount of NIS 1.2 million, which is made up of 40% of the prime interest track, the monthly repayment will rise by NIS 125.
How much has the average mortgage been increased since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, this has been a significantly sharper increase.
This is because the interest rates in the other tracks that make up a mortgage (and not just in the prime track) have also increased – in an index-linked track and in the fixed interest rate track.
If the interest rate does rise by half a percent, the increase will be NIS 620 in a mortgage of about NIS 1.2 million.
The prime track (40% in this track) will complete an increase of NIS 280, assuming there will be an increase of another 0.5% next month.
The variable interest rate track is linked to the index (26.7% in this track) will complete an increase of NIS 120.
The fixed interest rate track - not index-linked (33.3% in this track) will increase by NIS 220.
So what do you do today?
For those who have a mortgage that is mostly linked to the index, a bundle recommends considering recycling for tracks that are not linked.
For mortgage borrowers who have been significantly increased for them in a significant way and it is difficult for them to meet repayments - he recommends examining to refinance a mortgage and re-release it for a longer period.
This is to reduce payments despite the increase in interest rates, since it is always better to meet repayments and not be insolvency.
As for new mortgage takers - he highly recommends getting to know the different tracks and adjusting the mortgage to their economic capabilities.
The same is true in the future when interest rates fall, they will be able to refinance a mortgage with a minimum early repayment fee.
Regarding buyers of apartments from a contractor - Tzror recommends preceding payments to the contractor and taking out a mortgage now.
It should be taken into account that the "construction input index" significantly raises the price of the property even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The residential construction input price index rose by 6.6% in the past year.
Against the background of the increase in this index, the Banking Supervision Department announced that it was considering the creation of a mechanism that would allow the linkage to be included within the mortgages, but the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The price of fuel is increasing - and the Israelis will have to pay more than NIS 8 per liter in July
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of gasoline 95 octane will be NIS 8.08 •
At the same time, the reduction of half a NIS per liter will be extended by the end of 2022
A record of a decade: The price of gasoline will jump by 36 cents per liter - and will be more than NIS 8 per liter from July 1.
The new price per liter of gasoline 95 octane will be 8.08 and those who wish to enjoy full service will be required to pay another 21 cents per liter.
At the same time, the reduction of half a shekel per liter in the diesal tax will be extended by the end of 2022, the Tax Authority said.
As mentioned above, the price increase is due to the continued rise in oil prices, against the backdrop of the war between Russia and Ukraine and the rise in the dollar rate.
If it were not for the half-shekel discounted by the government since April, the price of fuel would have exceeded the all-time record – NIS 8.25 per liter.
The validity of the discount ends at the end of July and the Tax Authority and the Ministry of Finance are currently promoting a publication for public comments of an order extending the reduction in the tax on gasoline, which is about half a shekel per liter, until August 9.
In addition, starting on August 10, an additional reduction of another half shekels will be determined, so that only from this date the price of a liter of gasoline will be reduced by one shekel by November 15, 2022.
This was reported by the Tax Authority.
“We have reached a point where I do not remember for five months in a row of excess in the state’s revenue.
We started a few months ago with the issue of tax reduction on diesel fuel.
We are already working on an extension in four months of the Blue, Gasoline and Solizar tax – instead of half a shekel.
It's good for industry and citizen.
If we lower, it will affect inflation, reduce production and ease the cost of living.
As finance minister, despite the election campaign, I intend to focus first on this," Minister Lieberman said at the Horowitz Economics and Society conference of the Israel Democracy Institute.
To date, more than half of the price of fuel is the taxes charged by the government (Blee Tax and VAT) – and this is a high tax rate compared to most developed countries.
The price of fuel has a dramatic impact on the cost of living in the economy – because it affects both household expenses and business expenses, public transportation prices and flights, transportation costs, and more.
Third time in a row: Ashdod - the most friendly city for business
Petah Tikva came in second place in the Ministry of Economy's business work rankings •
After them: Rehovot, Ashkelon and Rishon LeZion •
Minister Barbibai: "The Corona emphasized the importance of local government in business development"
.
Ashdod is the most small and medium-sized business-friendly city.
For the third year in a row, the Business Industry Index in the local authorities of the Small and Medium Business Agency found in the Ministry of Economy and Industry, which ranked local authorities.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva and in third place is Rehovot.
Followed by: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Yafo, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Beer Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya and Bnei Brak.
The agency is editing the local authorities index.
This is the fifth time and its goal is to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance to other authorities in a variety of parameters, and to analyze its performance in the areas in which it is active.
The index is based on several parameters that are examined in each authority, which examine the level of the "friendliness" of the Business Authority in its field.
The index divides the authorities into three groups of size by number of residents, as a local authority of up to 50,000 residents is not like a local authority of more than 150 thousand residents.
Tel Aviv has jumped this year
The index is updated once a year and weighs four different rankings in each local authority: business satisfaction, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information and municipal taxes.
The rating shows that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth place, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to 12th place and Netanya dropped from fifth place to 13th.
A decline in the ranking does not mean that the Authority’s business service has deteriorated, and in many cases it stems from the fact that the service of other authorities for business has improved more and they have risen in the ranking, while the Authority that has decreased in the ranking has less improved its services for businesses.
Among the immigrants in the ranking are Petah Tikva, who rose from sixth place to second place, and streets that rose from 12th place to third place.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from fourth place to 11th place in 2019, improved in 2021 and rose to sixth place.
“Business – A Growth Engine”
The ranking shows that Nof Hagalil is a leader in local authorities, which include between 50 and 150 thousand residents.
Following is Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modiin-Maccabim-Reut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Karmiel, Afula and Hod HaSharon.
28th and last place is located in Tiberias.
“The index is intended to encourage local authorities to make it easier for small and medium-sized businesses, starting at the time of opening the business and throughout its activity with the authorities,” says Minister of Economy and Industry Orna Barbibai.
“Business is a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy and are responsible for about 50% of the business GDP and about 60% of those employed in the economy.
The development of small businesses is in the public interest of all of us, but the local authority has a direct impact on the businesses that are in it.
The coronavirus emphasized the importance of the local government and saw that authorities that operated and encouraged the advancement of small businesses and found creative solutions for them, became the first governmental interface for them.”
Ran Kuiti, director of the Small and Medium Business Agency at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: “Local authorities have a central and essential role in the ability of businesses in their field to thrive and flourish.
In the past two years, in which we are dealing with the Corona crisis, the authorities have greater weight in helping businesses to survive in their field and survive in general.”
2021 by mail: 20 packages per household - and a leap in weight
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020 •
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a 36% jump from 2020 •
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight was 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, almost 20 packages on average per household, according to Israel Post data obtained by Israel Hayom.
The number of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to 2020, in which 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and low from 2019, with 61.6 million packages.
However, this year there was a jump of more than 36% per year in the weight of the packages that came from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products from abroad arrived in Israel, a jump of 36%, compared to 14,860 tons in 2020, and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight for the package jumped 60% in two years—from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The surge in the weight of the packages is mainly influenced by two main trends, both on the seller and on the part of the buyer: the large shopping sites abroad combine items for one shipment and no longer send any product from the "shopping basket" in a separate package.
On the part of the Israeli consumer, the quick delivery of the shipments, within a few days of order, supports the purchase of more everyday products such as clothing and gifts, which the buyers wish to receive prior to the purchase.
Also in 2021, as in 2020 and 2019, the month when the most packages from abroad came at the highest weight and the highest number of items is December, with 4.2 million packages weighing 2,200 tons.
In December, the average weight per package was 524 grams, 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The Black Friday Effect
More packages came in December than any other month, probably following the November shopping holidays, such as Chinese Singles Day, Black Friday and Cyber Monday.
The big orders start arriving in Israel between one and two weeks after the purchase.
Study: Most employees in the economy are unaware that tax refunds can be received
Many employees deserve money from the state, which can reach tens of thousands of shekels •
Have you changed jobs?
Are you on vacation?
Did you move from the city to the town?
You may be entitled to receive a considerable amount of money in a simple procedure •
All the details - inside
Most employees are unaware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can accumulate to high amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report from two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds of NIS 3.6 billion, which means that you should also check whether you are entitled to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a large amount, since four out of five employees are entitled to tax refunds.
In practice, on the other hand, a few tens of thousands of employees are served annually.
If you think that these funds will go down the drain anyway, think again: Employees can apply for income tax for reimbursement for six years back.
Tax:On carried out in-depth research among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax refunds during 2020.
The company has more than 30 thousand customers, so the sample reflects their dispersion in terms of groups in the population and gender, ages and geography.
The data show that during 2020, due to the outbreak of the Corona crisis and the expenditure of hundreds of thousands of workers per shared, there were a number of significant changes, including a 15% increase in the amount of the average return to a household, which was NIS 4,300 a year.
The reason is that the leave fee is lower than the salaries and therefore a gap is created between what the employee paid as a tax and what he actually needs.
By the way, the highest refund received in 2020 a customer of the company was NIS 121,054 for refunds for the past 6 years.
What can I get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons for receiving tax refunds is a change in the workplace.
81% of people who exchanged a workplace during the year generated a tax refund of NIS 2,943.
Another reason is maternity leave.
The data show that 74% of women who gave birth and spent on maternity leave for more than 16 weeks were entitled to an average refund of NIS 3,538 for the same year.
Another reason for the refund is donations.
100% of people who donate and pay taxes have been refunded.
Another cause of refund is not to register credit points for alimony. 63%
The ex-hustles did not update a credit point for alimony and therefore the tax refund for each year that no such credit point has been updated is NIS 2,616.
Due to unemployment - expenditure per NIS: 93% of those who are going on challah or unemployment and who earned over NIS 12,000 received a tax refund of NIS 4021 for that year.
Additional reasons for tax refunds are: repayment for life insurance payments, mortgage life insurance, refund of eligible settlement, refund for losses in securities, failure to register credit points for a man for childbirth and distribution of tax refunds according to geographical location.
- 94% of people who deposited into personal life insurance or for taking out a mortgage were entitled to a tax refund.
In an examination conducted for every million shekels from a mortgage for 25 years, the cumulative tax refund for the period is over NIS 20,000 for the entire mortgage period.
100% of those who move to a qualifying community received a tax refund for the transfer year since the approval of residency in the eligible community is given only after 12 months from the date of becoming an eligible resident and thus in fact the first year is paid full tax.
79% of customers holding securities were entitled to a refund of the said years tax.
However, anyone who owns securities is important to check every year since losses are not rolled from year to year but only through the submission of a report.
56% of men who have a child do not record credit points in the year of birth in the pay slip.
The refund rate can reach tens of thousands of shekels over 6 years.
This is a phenomenon that exists mainly in the Arab sector.
Tax Director:on, Tal Carmon: “The coronavirus crisis has caused the Israeli public to become much more active.
He's interested, checking and demanding what he deserves in income tax refunds.
It turns out that sitting at home, in the leave or after the dismissal, of hundreds of thousands of Israelis for many months, has caused many employees to examine in depth what they deserve from the state.
It is important to know that today all the procedures can be carried out to receive tax refunds digitally, easy and simple, without the bureaucracy that has deterred many in the past.”
Employment market: fewer candidates for the job, more salary
Oljobs Report to Summary 2021: Top of Demand - Jobs Without Experience •
The number of jobs offered increased by 50% •
“Looking for work, but don’t charge the market.”
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decline in the number of resumes sent, and each position was run on average by only 23 candidates, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year, according to a report by the Oljobs website to summarize 2021, on the coronavirus crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were mainly interested in job-saturated areas such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, the jobs without experience led to demand with more than 38,000 searches – probably following the return of young people with no professional experience to search for immediate work, at the end of the unpaid leave payments.
The number of sales and administrative searches was 35 thousand and 32 thousand (respectively), drivers and messengers had 11 thousand searches, and the preservation had slightly less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the Corona crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was NIS 11,675 gross.
The monthly salary in the software field was an average of NIS 17,915, and in the analysis of information systems it was NIS 17,140.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a salary gap of more than NIS 2,000: in the center of the country it was an average of NIS 12,500, compared to NIS 10,795 in the north and NIS 10,135 in the south.
From a gender point of view, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained in the type of work and in the volume of hours, was maintained and stood at 36%.
Men earned NIS 13,295, compared to the women's salary of NIS 9,740.
Trying to get back to the line
On the side of the business, there was a cross-growth growth in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses longed for working hands.
Thus, the job offerings increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40 thousand jobs in Aljubs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase the total funding but 72% understand that they would find it difficult this year.
The largest supply was for jobs without experience – and there were more than 58 thousand on the site.
Afterwards, there were customer service and administrative positions with about 44 thousand jobs in each field, sales and software with 41 thousand jobs each, teaching and education with 24 thousand vacancies, and vaccinators are still in demand in 19 thousand vacancies.
Einav Boymfeld, Director of Research and Content at Oljubs: “Work Seekers are trying to return to the line but do not charge the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the prolonged disconnection from the workforce makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to make a living.”
The unemployment rate in Israel has risen to 6.3%
According to the Ministry's survey data, about 270,000 Israelis were left out of work in December 2021 •
In November, there were about 262 thousand unemployed.
The percentage of unemployed in the first half of December 2021 was 6.3%, about 270 thousand Israelis, compared to 6.1% in the second half of November 2021 (about 262 thousand).
