In addition, the auditor recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activity – and to update the procedures of the basket work •
Another defect that has been found to concern that since the committee began operations, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the scope of the uses and the utilization of the drugs in the basket – which would have allowed to analyze and control the budget given to them.
The Medicines Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees in our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the HMOs – but a new report by the State Comptroller published on Tuesday warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without conducting control reports on its activities and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council monitoring and examining its activities.
A reporter "Israel Hayom," Ran Reznik, adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing exposures in Israel Hayom on the failures of the basket of medicines.
According to Netanyahu Engelman’s report, he recommends “in the process of expanding the basket, repairs and improvements, which will lead to a higher quality exhaustion of the health basket budget that the public is entitled to.”
Throughout the years of the existence of the supplement mechanism for the medicine basket, in the years 1998 and NIS 8 billion of drugs were added to the state budget – with the addition moving annually in amounts ranging from NIS 0 to NIS 500 million.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021 applications were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare basket, at an annual cost of more than two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated to expand the basket was less than the scope of the applications.
In most years of the committee's operation (90% of the time), the amount of the budgetary supplement was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired supplement rate.
The auditor notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual addition in order to enable certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman added that “the model of transparency in the work of the basket is lacking.”
Thus, for example, the procedure of the basket committee determines that the conference protocols, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the protocols are published with a delay of 160-109 days, when sometimes the final meetings protocols are not published at all.
“The delay in the publication of the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; because of this, the ability of the bidders – the patient organizations and the pharmaceutical companies – may be impaired as soon as possible and relevant, after drawing lessons from rejecting their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and corrected their proposals and reassessed their acceptance of them in the next round,” the comptroller said.
“The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set out in the procedure.”
Out of thousands of submissions, only one financial comment was submitted
Another Engelman review concerns the preliminary process of assessing the technologies submitted to the medicine basket.
The comptroller found that about half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this phase, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the grounds for rejection.
Another impairment relates to the activity of the subcommittee of the basket of drugs that is closed to the media and the public, in which patients' numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The comptroller recommends attaching a public representative or examining the possibility of publishing the discussions to the public without confidential commercial details.
In the procedure according to which the Health Services Basket Committee is working, it was determined that “economic evaluation must be submitted” to the request to add a cure to the basket.
But in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment has been submitted out of thousands of submissions – and the committee makes its decisions without financial evaluation.
For example, for the 2021-2019 basket committee hearings, applications were submitted to add anti-obesity medicines to the basket.
The report found that no economic assessments were attached to the requests, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing damage from diseases originating in obesity or due to the ability to avoid gastric shortening surgery.
It also shows that the decisions of the Medicines Basket Committee are inconsistent with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, the Ministry of Health defined in 2019 the preventive medicine and preparations for the treatment of tumors of chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, there was no emphasis on the need to achieve these goals.
The comptroller also warns that since 2011, the medicines have also included services that are not under the responsibility of the health funds, including various rehabilitation and mobility and mobility devices and vaccines, which are provided by the Ministry of Health (the “third supplement”).
This is when the legal framework for this step is regulated only in retrospect.
In the past six years, NIS 74 million has been used from the addition to the basket of medicines for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the procedures of the basket work and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the medicine basket are defined as “drugs without additional cost”, the use of which does not cost the health plans for an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The auditor proposes to examine the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and abbreviated track, so that the basket of drugs can be updated several times a year and not just once a year.
There is no supervision over the use of expensive medicines.
The audit also shows that since the work of the basket committee began 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health did not ask the health plans to report and did not supervise the scope of the uses and exploitation of the drugs in the basket, information that could have allowed the Ministry to analyze and control the budget given to the health plans.
Over the years, only two reports have been published that relate to the years 2009-2006, and these were also published significantly late (the latter was published this year and dealt with the use of the budget in 2009-2007).
“The delay in carrying out tests may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, to the irrelevance of the conclusions that arise from the examination after such a long period, to the optimal pricing of the subcommittee and to make decisions based on non-final findings,” the report said.
In addition, the Ministry also does not criticize and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not made lessons learned.
This is 10 drugs that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in 2021-2016).
To this, the comptroller wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the scope of their use compared to the estimates.
Controls and analysis will enable the conclusions of systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the subcommittee, and how to prepare the estimates during the pricing of the drugs and technologies and improve them.”
