Medical Malpractice in the Different Stages of Birth
In order to receive compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused due to the same negligence
Birth is one of the most joyous and exciting events in a family’s life.
Unfortunately, however, births often end with serious damage caused by the mother or the newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended with physical injury, newborn or mother, there is room to examine the sequence of events that have led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical malpractice will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical staff in the various stages of birth that caused the damage and if he saw fit he will turn to consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every mistake in treatment on the part of the medical staff arises in the malpractice (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that management was negligent.
When is it negligence?
When the doctor’s mistake was due to a lack of skill or veered from the reasonable level of caution, and the incompetence and deviation from the accepted level of caution caused damage to the patient who would not have been caused had it not been for the doctor’s driver.
In this article we will examine the different stages of birth, explain what are the complications that may occur in each of the stages and when they arise to medical malpractice.
Stage of contractions
The contraction phase lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix is gradually opened (in order to allow the passage of the fetus at birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most medical malpractice cases in the contraction stage deal with the failure to identify fetal distress before birth, which caused damage to the newborn, which is sometimes manifested in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by non-recognition or delay in identifying a sublivarian shaft, which is reflected in the failure of oxygen supply to the fetal brain tissue.
As a rule, monitoring the mother's condition and correctly deciphering the monitor that monitors the activity of the fetal heart should lead to early detection of the development of fetal distress, which allows the medical staff to act quickly and rescue the newborn before irreversibly injured.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus suffers from a lack of oxygen or that the staff does not correctly interpret data in front of it, and especially the fetal monitor or responds late to the distress expressed in the monitor, may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by the prolapse of the umbilical cord and as a result of a uterine rupture that was not detected in the time.
Even in these difficult events, it is appropriate to find out whether the medical staff acted properly.
For example, Adv. Anna Reif Liegenza, from Caspi Saror & Co., who specializes in representing medical malpractice victims, said that her office handled the claim of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife expired the amniotic sac when the fetal head was too high, thus leading to the navel rope prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the fetal head) and damage to the oxygen supply to the fetal brain (as a result of pressure on the umbil cord).
In another case, the lawyer said that her office filed a lawsuit due to serious medical malpractice of the staff of the maternity department in a large hospital that during childbirth did not identify at the time clear signs that required real suspicion that the mother suffers from a rupture of the uterine in the surgical scar area of her previous pregnancy.
The fetus that was ejected through the rupture in his mother's uterus into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until it was delayed at a late stage when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that in order to receive compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the squirrel and the damage caused to the newborn, meaning that the damage was caused by such negligence and not from any other reason or factor.
The examination of the causal relationship will be carried out by examining medical indicators that according to the medical literature only in their existence there is a causal connection between the shanish and the brain injury.
Among other things, the indices of the level of acidity in the fetus's blood, its apgar scores, the existence of a neurological and systemic injury, and more.
Death of the Fetus
The active stage of birth
The active stage of birth begins when the opening of the cervix reaches a diameter of 10 cm and ends at the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Deliference at birth and avoidance of performing a C-section
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., a lack of progression of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a C-section, in order to prevent various damages that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay at birth.
“There are cases in which failure to perform a cesarean section in a timely manner can cause irreparable damage to the fetus,” Rafe-Ligenza explained to us.
“For example, we conducted a medical malpractice claim for childbearing death caused by a significant delay in performing a C-section.
Unlike any recognized medical practice, medical staff members did not recognize the fetal distress and perform a C-section despite the particularly slow progress of the birth.
The delay in performing the operation caused extensive systemic damage to the birth, which eventually led to her death shortly after her birth.”
Negligence in vacuum birth
In situations where a mother or fetus is in a significant danger that requires a particularly quick termination of the birth, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed (a vacuum tuber).
In this process, a vacuum is attached to the petus' head and pull the fetus out by force.
Naturally, this action involves dangers and may cause damage to both the fetus and the mother and therefore requires great care, accuracy and skill.
In these events, medical malpractice may be expressed in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the binding guidelines and performs the operation despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the head of the fetus is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for a longer time than permitted or when despite the failure of a large number of attempts, the doctor continues to repeat the procedure more than the number of attempts allowed.
In these cases, if the negligent vacuum action has caused the newborn damage – among other things, it can cause rudge damage and bleeding that may cause the development of brain damage – there is room for filing a tort claim.
ERB Paralysis
Arb paralysis is a congenital nerve injury to the brachial plexus (a nerve node that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth it is worth checking whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetric staff.
The injury is manifested by the weakness of the hands muscles and can reach up to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of a 'should disorder' - an obstetric emergency that occurs when the fetus's shoulders are trapped in the face of the birth canal after its head is released.
When should you suspect that the paralysis is caused by medical malpractice?
In cases where the weight assessment of the fetus indicated that it is a macrosomy embryo, that is, it is expected to be born at a weight exceeding 4.5 kilograms and in accordance with the instructions, it is better to deliver the mother by cesarean section.
When the weight of the newborn is over 4 kg, a C-section should be considered in light of the risk factors, including gestational diabetes and the elongation of the second stage of birth.
In the event that the medical staff ignores an abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or from other risk factors and chooses to continue vaginal birth and the risk of ERB shoulder disorder and paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical malpractice.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that “the risk that during childbirth will occur shoulder stenosis can be predicted in advance to some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is a concern for its occurrence is to conduct a C-section.”
Placenta exit stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the newborn and is accompanied by bleeding.
The process takes up to half an hour in most cases from the moment of the baby's departure and according to a large part occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the placenta left, the medical team will check whether it left in its entirety or whether there are parts of the placenta left in the womb.
Within this stage, there may be complications that can cause serious damage to the mother.
One of the familiar complications from the remainder of placenta residue in the uterus is called "Asherman syndrome", the scarring of the uterine wall scarring the result of inflammation caused by the remaining placenta residue in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the endometrium in a way that does not allow pregnancy rooting.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not identify that there were latile residue left or did not take all measures to prevent harm to the endometrium despite the suspicion of the leftovers in the uterus, it may be medical malpractice and the case is suitable for a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Death of the mother
The death of a mother during childbirth is a rather rare euro.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the whole family unfortunately becomes the most tragic event for it.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother on time or reacts late to such bleeding.
"For example,...", Attorney Reif-Lignaza said to us, "Our firm filed a lawsuit concerning the death of a mother, when in that case the medical staff ignored and did not respond to the mother's worrying vital bookmark, for long hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrollable bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the background disease from which she suffered."
"In another case...", Attorney Reif-Lignaza said, "Our firm represented the relatives of a mother who died after the birth of twins due to a bleeding originating in the section of the C-section that was not properly sewn.
In that case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after surgery, but the medical staff did not properly address her complaints and her clinical condition, reacted late only after her body systems began to collapse, which led to her death.”
Loss of womb
In severe cases, medical malpractice may lead to a hysterectomy, says Adv. Rafe Lingza: "Our firm has conducted a claim against a hospital that is based on a hysterectomy due to medical malpractice after birth.
In the same case, the mother, a 31-year-old woman, lost her womb due to a lack of proper treatment for massive bleeding observed by the medical staff after birth and yet they were not taken during the actions that could prevent the damage.
What are the compensations awarded in claims for medical malpractice at birth?
Childhood compensation for injury due to medical malpractice at birth includes many damage components, with the most significant sums being given for pain and suffering, long-term care and caring for wages, salary losses and pensions for the injured person and even his parents and other damage components.
The compensation awarded to a damaged minor for salary and pension losses is calculated in most cases on the basis of the average wage in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical accessories and rehabilitation, the cost of adapting housing to the baby's needs, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case and according to its circumstances," says Adv. Reif-Lignanza, and she adds, noting that "today most of the claims on the grounds of medical malpractice end in a compromise that considers the chance and risk that each party has in the conduct of the proceeding," the attorney added, adding that "there are cases in which the proceeding ends only in a judgment, so if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages.Compensation exceeds ten million shekels.”
In conclusion
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly the nightmare of every family.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic result, by a skilled lawyer in managing claims on the grounds of medical malpractice, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
