Study: Zoom Meetings Harm Creativity
About 2,100 engineers and academics around the world have been asked to develop solutions to the problem – some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings •
The result: a virtual meeting damages creativity and thinking outside the box •
Columbia University Research Leader: "The Visual Focus on the Screen Hurts the Process of Ideas"
Nechama Porta: There is no harm to the productivity of the work or critical thinking.
A large scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of meetings through video software on the creativity of their participants, compared to face-to-face sessions.
Unfortunately, creativity has been found to have been compromised in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question – led by Melanie Brooks, a professor’s assistant from Columbia University – was whether remote computer meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free thinking decreases as a result of the distance.
The study itself began in 2016 but received a big boost in the two years of the coronavirus, during which many employees moved to work from home.
“People in a personal meeting are pleasant in the room, use objects and use them for creative thinking,” Brooks says.
“In a computer meeting, however, the concentration in maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces the cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which harms the broad and broad-expanding process of idea creation.”
Space is shrinking.
To examine the results of the experiment and verify whether to repeat themselves, they were tested twice – once at Columbia University and once again in real life – about engineers who knew each other from prior acquaintance.
The university distributed a group of 602 faculty members and students to two parts – in one the examinees were asked to meet personally and develop solutions to the problem, and in the other they were asked to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to divide in a similar way and solve a new way a problem presented to them.
In both cases, there was a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually in video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher who deals with ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their environment to use the creation of ideas, while in a video session, the thinking converges into the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
“When people in the same room, they look around and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can trigger new associations in them.
On the other hand, research shows that relationships through a computer change our attention so that we are more focused inward and screen, and this way reduces innovation and creating ideas by looking at the environment and thinking outwards.”
There is no harm to critical thinking.
However, and before managers run employees back to the offices, the researchers note that “work through a computer did not harm productivity itself and not in people’s critical thinking about innovative offers, when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the harm is focused on creativity only and not for the rest of the ways of working in front of a computer.”
Professor Alan Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also retires the findings.
“There’s a difference between just creativity, like new uses for the Frisbee (one of the research questions; EG) and work solutions.
It is also possible that when the employees are more relaxed after getting to know each other, or that they work from home, creativity will improve.”
Both Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson have also proposed future research in which such meetings will be discontinued into thinking and wandering situations in the room to see how this activity will affect the final result.
Dr. Olson also suggested that following the study only for brainstorming sessions, employees would return to work and in general he suggested not to be alarmed by one study but to carry out another investigation in the field.
“I wouldn’t want workers to be forcibly returned and not happy is a greater blow,” he says.
