By 2050: The world will lose 80% of the water available for agriculture
A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years
The Solution: Proper Management of Water Reservoirs
A recent new study published in Earth’s Future predicts that by 2050, the amount of water available to agriculture will decrease by about 80% if the rate of water consumption and the growth of the world’s population will remain in their current usage trends.
In the study, which was attended by scientists from all the world’s science agencies, scientists concluded the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to humanity’s need in agriculture.
The grim conclusions of the study show that as of now the rate of water consumption doubles over and over again in the past 10 years, while at the same time global warming causes the amount of rainfall in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the study’s data, 84% of the land intended for agriculture around the world will experience a severe shortage of rainwater.
One of the main conclusions that emerged from the study calls on farmers around the world to adapt agriculture to climate change and the seasons, and to switch to growing methods that will make it easier for water to penetrate the soil in order to prevent the process of evaporating water that will lead to widespread waste of rainwater.
In addition, the researchers advise farmers working near saltwater sources to use rainwater collection technologies to prevent their flow to the sea.
